example.p:
Convert each radical to exponential notation.

\sqrt[3]{12} = 12^{1/3}

\sqrt[4]{2y} = (2y)^{1/4} \text{ or } (2y)^{0.25}

webwork.pg-code:
Context(Fraction)->functions->disable("All");
Context()->variables->add(a=>"Real", b=>"Real", w=>"Real");
Context()->flags->set(limits=>[2,5]);
$f = Formula("(ab)**(-1/5)");
$g = Formula("3*w^(1/6)");

example.p:
Convert each power to radical notation.

5^{1/2} = \sqrt{5}

x^{0.2} = \sqrt[5]{x}

2x^{1/3} = 2 \sqrt[3]{x}

8a^{-1/4} = \dfrac{8}{\sqrt[4]{a}}

webwork.pg-code:
            $A =  RadioButtons(
                    ["\( \dfrac{3}{2x^{1/4}} \)",
                    "\(3 (2x)^{-1/4} \)",                    
                    "\( \dfrac{3}{2}x^{-1/4} \)",
                    ], 
                    1
                );
            $B =  RadioButtons(
                    ["\(\sqrt[8]{-5b}\)",
                    "\(-\sqrt[5]{b^8}\)",
                    "\(-5\sqrt[8]{b}\)",
                    ], 
                    2
                );
# setting the context to force students to use exponential format for (a)
# would prevent students from entering radical format for (b)

subsection.p:
Figure (a) shows the graphs of 
    y = x^{1/2}, ~~y = x^{1/4},~~ \text{and} ~~y = x^{1/6} 

Figure (b) shows the graphs of 
    y = x^{1/3},~~ y = x^{1/5},~~ \text{and}~~ y = x^{1/7}

We will also encounter power functions with negative exponents. For example, an animal's heart rate is related to its size or mass, with smaller animals generally having faster heart rates. The heart rates of mammals are given approximately by the power function
    H(m) = km^{-1/4}
where m is the animal's mass and k is a constant.

